segments.text: When did you, when and where did you go back to school?
Okay, I came back in April 46, discharged at Camp Atterbury, 10 miles from Franklin, Indiana, where my mother and father had lived at one time, and I was related to about a third of the county.
I came back and decided to go back and finish my dissertation on G.I.
Bill.
This was the
It paid my expenses, and what was it, $80 or $90 a month, and all my dissertation costs, et cetera, et cetera.
And you don't get much leave while war is going on, so I had almost three months of leave to accumulate and got a certain amount of cash.
I'd finished my dissertation.
It worked out fine.
But when I finished it, I was the second PhD in Chicago from about 1942 to finish.
Everybody had gone in.
So I had a doctoral thing.
you know, your doctoral committee normally.
I had my sitting in my, everybody wanted to sit in on a doctoral exam.
Nobody had been in one except Al Summitt who had preceded me, who's been president of Southern Illinois later.
Here are the people who, I made a list once of who was on my dissertation.
board and sat and why they passed me I'll never know.

Leonard White, Herman Pritchett, Walter Johnson, head of the history department, Morton Grodson, then head of political science, Don Price, Albert Lepofsky, head of the Finance Officers Association, James Mitchell, later civil service commissioner, Jerome Kerwin, political theory, Charles Harden,
Avery Leiserson, Hans Morgenthau, Lindsay Wright, and Alfred Cobbett.
Oh, my.
That was a who's who.
Oh, dear.
And I'd been away from school for five years.
So I always think of one.
Cobbett asked me, I'd lived in France, would I care to comment on the experience of the French government after the war?
I thought, oh, God.
I said, no, I wouldn't.
And I got away with it.
They passed me, I think, by the...
I could answer questions on the dissertation all right, but nobody read it.
This crowd, they didn't have a clue about the history of the U.S. Civil Service.
Leonard White did, but...
So... At the first job, where was it?
My first job, I interviewed at Princeton, Purdue, Northwestern,
And everybody was looking for people, so there was a job.
And I was offered most at Purdue, but I went to Northwestern.
What was the first, that beginning size?
And what did that?
It wasn't bad.
That seemed like a pretty good sum, didn't it?
Yeah.
And this is as an instructor.
They didn't do assistant professors yet.
That took another 5, 10 years before a PhD could start as assistant professor.
So I was made assistant professor two years later.
Then I decided I wanted to get a bit of experience in the civil service.
So I took the exam for management analyst and passed it.
And 51 and 2, I spent as a GS-12 management analyst in the Office of the Comptroller of the Army as a civil servant.
In Washington?
In Washington.
Doing studies of the supply operations in the military.
And became, at the end, a section chief in the

that when Ed Litchfield, who was General Secretary of Political Science, who had been and was, or had just come back from being head of the Civil Administration Division of German Military Government under General Clay.
And Litchfield had just been appointed Dean of the new School of Business and Public Administration at Cornell.
And I had done a program for Litchfield while I was at Northwestern.
I had the first group of Germans into the United States for training in democracy.
We had about a dozen state and local government officials.
And I set up a program with the help of the public administration, clearinghouse people, Louis Brownlow and Herbert Emmerich, and some of the Chicago faculty.
We had the program beginning lecture discussion part at the University of Chicago.
And then we sent them out in the field.
Three of them, they'd heard about that the Indian had been so badly treated.
So I sent them up to the Cherokee Reservation in northern Wisconsin to see this terrible treatment they were getting.
And so one of the greatest help to me was T.V.
Smith.
who had worked with Germans.
And he clued me in on a, and I have a small volume that he did, which has never been published, I don't know why not, on kind of background.
He said the problem that the Germans have to face is if you are right,
How can you compromise?
This is the problem in European politics for the most part.
They speak of the French as being very logical.
They're so goddamn logical they never can agree.
And they said they're perfectly right.
The ethics of compromise are a bit peculiar.
So we faced that head on.
TV had a book, and they said you can in fact do a great many things without coming up into ethical problems if you will do so.
So I got two or three people in talking on that kind of problem.
public service, the public administration task, then back to academics?
Yes, I was on leave for a semester at Northwestern, then back to Northwestern, then to Washington, and then to Cornell.
I came to Cornell the fall of 52 and was there for 18 years.
Ed made me an offer of
five-year term appointment as associate professor, and that looked fine to me.
So I was making up lost time.
And I got appointed full professor in 1958.
Now, how did you and A&M link up?
In 63, I became national general secretary of Beta Theta Pi.
Our general secretary is a part-time official.
We have a full-time person in the headquarters.
We did it that way unusually.
Most of the attorneys tended to fall in the hands of the full-time permanent secretary.
Well, our chief administrative officer is a private citizen, part-time general secretary, and most of the work is done by volunteers rather than by full-time people.
So I agreed to do that.
I had the interesting situation.
My president was Dean Malott, who was a Kansas Spatha.
My dean was Bill Carmichael,
who had married Owen D. Young's granddaughter, and Owen D. Young was a St. Lawrence beta, and Philip Young's daughter.
He'd been dean of business in Columbia, and he was a beta.
So my dean was not a beta, but his daughter, his wife.
So I had my deans okay, and the presidents okay to do this.
I still taught my courses, but I got some extra space and a secretary and so on.
So I was general secretary at Bethlehem DePauw for a term.
Well, in 64, fortunately, when I became that, I had agreed to be general secretary, other things, and pull out two terms, other things being equal.
Well, I got engaged to Dorothy in 64 and I reported to the board, I'm sorry, things are no longer equal.
So I have Dorothy and I have a 13 year old stepson.
And so I finish that and end my work with beta theta pi for a while because
As general secretary, I had to sit in a board meeting being presided over by my predecessor, who had been made president.
And I figured, and who's a very able man, but with whom, very conservative, and I knew the fraternities had to expand.
And I was all the time, in effect,
trying to overturn his policies so I decided I will not be around while my successor is Joe Ramota who was dean of faculty at Saint Lawrence succeeded me and
So I stayed out of fraternity affairs for quite a bit until we got a chapter here and I got involved and I was their advisor for about six, seven years.
Well, that was running a large nonprofit organization, the Volunteers, is also an interesting experience.
And so,
We got my stepson through high school.
He'd been moved enough.
So we got him through Ithaca High School, and he was admitted into Syracuse.
And he could have gotten in the College of Agriculture at Cornell, but that didn't much interest him.
He didn't have quite good enough grades
make the College of Liberal Arts.
So, I decided eighteen winners, eighteen Ithaca winners is enough.
I was quite happy at Cornell.
I was getting a bit irked with the faculty who had, I think in 67 or 68, brought up
This is military unrest in Vietnam.
For about the fourth time brought up the question, do we allow the ROTC?
And I thought, four times is enough of that.
Cornell is heavily governed by its faculty, in distinction to a lot of institutions.
So I began to look around.
I had been out to Willamette to do a, they were interested in founding a school of business and public administration.
And the Chicago Beta was on their board of trustees and knew my background in the Cornell.
Would I come out and do a study for them?
Was this feasible?
And I talked to one of our Cornell professors who is now Dean of Business at Oregon.
And so I knew I could get him.
What are their plans?
Well, they had no money to expand and weren't interested in expanding.
So there wasn't going to be any.
Portland was in no shape to do anything.
So Willamette, being at the state capitol, was a natural for the PA part of it.
And it looked like they would have no great competition in the business side.
So I made a recommendation.
And of course, I was asked if I wanted to be dean of that, which I declined.
They're too far away.
And besides Willamette was a teetotaling school and too many other.
I didn't want to live that kind of life anyway.
And I was a long way from Washington.
So University of Georgia was
interested in talking, and I interviewed for a dean of the college at Georgia Tech and came close.
I was interviewed for residency of Colgate and Miami University, Oxford, Ohio, and was told in both places I was close.
After that, things were looking
messy, so in the university world I decided no more of this kind of look-see.
So one of the professors at Georgia recommended me to the people looking here.
So I got a letter from Texas A&M.
Who was the letter from?
Who was the real contact?
The letter was from, oh, this is from Hubert's, Hubert's office or somewhere.
And was it still Arts and Sciences, or was it just Liberal Arts then?
Liberal Arts, yeah, as I remember.
And his associate dean, I still see, McCandless.
So I was invited down and brought Dorothy down with me.
And as I began to see things and to see the colleges, most private schools and public schools were having financial problems by 1970.
And A&M was not.
And almost the weekend I came down to visit Ruddy had his stroke and died.
So I am interviewed by Hubert.
who is the dean of both education and liberal arts, and I think I'm about his last department head appointment.
What was your, as you think back about that interview, describe the Hubert as an interviewer?
Well, I wasn't interviewed much by Hubert.
I was interviewed in the department.
The department had
been formed in 68, out of history, as you know.
And William, well, he ought to remain nameless, had been there for a year from the Foreign Service.
Yeah, I can't remember his name either.
And I can give you the name, but in light of what I'm going to say, it's just as well we'll skip that.
nice guy, Ph.D. Princeton out of the Foreign Service.
And the problem was he didn't know anything about academia.
Well, be that as it may, but my main interview was with the faculty, and I remember myI'm
And I decided, you know, one doesn't talk about one's dissertation.
So I said, I'll open with a pronouncement, and then if you don't like it, don't hire me.
This is the time when the behavioral and traditional are fighting in the social sciences, and particularly in political science.
Cornell had been split over it.
Berkeley was split over it.
I said, I just want to comment on this.
I said, as to this kind of fight, I want to make it clear.
I've done a history than which you cannot be more traditional.
Now, I said, I've also just finished with the sociologist Lloyd Warner the study of American federal executives.
which is the largest questionnaire interview study anybody's ever done.
And with 1,300,000 pieces of data on punch cards and all the apparatus that goes with it.
Now I said, it was very interesting to find that
All of our propositions for which we used the punch card data to demonstrate, most of them came from the history.
Now I said, I'm quite convinced you need both sides of this coin and I will raise hell with anybody who wants to make a fight about it.
And so with that pronouncement, we had a very nice discussion and I was hired.
I wrote Hubert.
I said their salary is $1,000 or $2,000 too low, and he gave me another $1,000.
All right, now this would be the last salary question.
What was the beginning?
Yeah.
When you came to visit, you met with Hubert and the search committee.
Anyone else?
I'm trying to remember.
Mr.
Rudder was already...
He's out of it.
All right.
I think I had a visit with... Byers as the chief academic officer?
I don't think anybody...
I visited anybody up there at that time.
I think they were relying enough chaos in the operational on with Rudder's...
Rudder's just died.
Mm-hmm.
And enough chaos that nobody, I think it's left to Hubert.
What was your, for you and your wife, what were your impressions of A&M and of this community?
Well, Dorothy thought, oh, God.
She's from the east.
And while she and I are first cousins once removed, she knows Indiana and all.
brought up in Miami, Florida, which is East Coast Jewish, if anything.
As she said, she walked along and people said hello to her.
Her view of this howdy business was an invasion of privacy.
So she wasn't so sure, but she was willing to do it.
I came down a second time and took my
life in my hands, and I bought, she hadn't seen it, the house across the street.
I said, we're interested in old houses.
They began to show me 30s and 40s and 50s.
I said, haven't you got anything 19th century?
Well, she said, there is one, but it might be on the market.
The Wilson House, it's in an estate, it's about to be settled, and...
I went in it, and the price was $20,000.
I could have knocked down another five, I think, but I was so astonished because such things in Ithaca, they were already being snapped up.
Texas is, you know, housing-wise, ten years behind.
And $20,000, I thought, I can't believe it.
This is intact.
painted canvas walls, crystal chandeliers, lovely woodwork.
It needs a little foundation work.
It's pier and beamed, but everything's there, and 20,000, I can't believe it.
So I'm in it 20 minutes and said, I'll take it.
And I took my, as they say, my life in my hands because Dorothy liked it.
But I'd bought it without her.
Now, this is late spring 1970.
This is late spring 1970.
And so you all arrived when?
Okay, part of my deal with Hubert was that there was no money for travel transportation down.
So I got the...
salary, half salary, all of my July salary.
I didn't have to report till early August, but I got paid for July.
And so we arrived in the early August.
Did anyone give you any guidelines as to what they expected?
Next to none.
What dreams did anyone have for the department from any sort?
Well, my predecessor had set out deliberately to make it a behavioral department.
That's the interesting thing is he was a PhD in international relations from Princeton with no background whatever in numerical quantitative stuff.
a most unlikely candidate.
He had set out to...
He'd gotten in the budget money for a distinguished professor.
And he then was trying to make life difficult for Gene Benton.
I was going to be six weeks late getting there, so I designated the senior professor as acting head without consulting anybody else.
I didn't think I needed to.
And Gene Benton was the acting head, and I get a call from my predecessor desperately, a phone call in Ithaca, what do I mean by making Benton acting head?
He's going to ruin me.
And I find out that he's been trying to get rid of Benton.
He deprived me of an office, of a telephone, and making life as difficult as possible.
He said, Benton's going to crucify me.
I said, if he does, give me a ring and we will take care of that problem.
But meanwhile, Benton is staying as acting kid.
And there was no problem.
Gene was too nice a guy.
So I had made my position clear.
No, it was very funny.
I really had no directions particularly at all and no pressures anywhere.
Did you have some goals when you got here?
Well, I began to figure some out fairly quickly.
This is a brand new department.
One thing that interests me is that you don't often get a blank page on which to write in academia.
I had been lucky at Cornell in on the founding, essentially.
I was there two years after the school opened.
Well, two years after the first graduating class, and it was still being formed.
and then here.
And so by the end of the summer, David Maxwell is coming on as Hubert's replacement.
Dean of Liberal Arts.
Yeah.
Maxwell is interested in some forward planning.
But I have no particular directions from Maxwell.
I'm as old as he is, and he figures, I think, that I've got some notions, maybe.
I said, look, Dean, I want about six months to get familiar with the school.
I said, this is not unlike Cornell.
In fact, it was exactly the same size as Cornell when we came here.
And a land grant institution.
I was well aware of that.
Except the College of Liberal Arts of Cornell was always, it was the center of the university's strength.
Well, it never had been here.
So, first thing I did, I have about 30,000 in for a
full professor in the budget that hasn't been filled.
I've come, but I'm in the head slot.
And I said, Dean Maxwell, look, I'm in a funny situation here.
My predecessor had designed a PhD program.
He had
put it through the winter of 69 to Huber.
Except one of the last things Huber did before he left was disapprove it.
Meanwhile, my predecessor has offered and they've accepted six assistantships to prospective PhD students.
They're here, and no PhD.
And what's more, no prospects of one.
What possessed my predecessor to think he could get one, he only had Benton, Rowe, and himself as possible members of a graduate faculty.
And to do a PhD on that is
So I said, Dean, I want to start building this from young people.
I don't want to bring in on top of them.
I don't want to discourage them.
With young people, I said, my predecessor has done one thing well.
He has brought four or five young assistant professors here who are good.
Gary Holder is one, Dixon, Bob Bernstein.
I don't know whether any of these, you know Holder, of course.
A fellow who was, when I was coming, decided he better maybe, he wasn't so sure he went, but he was good enough that Rice took him.
And another one went to maybe LSU.
